s://books.google.com/books?id=or8LOAAACAAJ The Baseball Talmud: The Definitive Position-by-Position Ranking of Baseball's Chosen Players]'', Howard Megdal, Collins, 2009, {{ISBN|0-06-155843-5}}\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=irG7GQAACAAJ The New Big Book of Jewish Baseball: An Illustrated Encyclopedia & Anecdotal History]'', Peter S. Horvitz, Joachim Horvitz, Perseus Distribution Services, 2007, {{ISBN|1-56171-821-1}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=qJEQTaE7JEAC ''Jews and Baseball: Entering the American mainstream, 1871\u20131948''], Burton Alan Boxerman, Benita W. Boxerman, McFarland, 2006, {{ISBN|0-7864-2828-7}}\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=9ZzxydPInwgC The Big Book of Jewish Baseball: An Illustrated Encyclopedia & Anecdotal History]'', Peter S. Horvitz, Joachim Horvitz, SP Books, 2001, {{ISBN|1-56171-973-0}}\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-BMAAAACAAJ The Jewish Baseball Hall of Fame: a Who's Who of Baseball Stars]'', Erwin Lynn, Shapolsky Publishers, 1986, {{ISBN|0-933503-17-2}}\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=G2o8AAAACAAJ Jewish Baseball Stars]'', Harold Uriel Ribalow, Meir Z. Ribalow, Hippocrene Books, 1984, {{ISBN|0-88254-898-0}}\n* \"Sandy Koufax: Pitcher Nonpareil and Perfect Gentleman\". In ''American Jews and America's Game: Voices of a Growing Legacy in Baseball'', [[Larry Ruttman]], University of Nebraska Press, 2013, {{ISBN|978-0-8032-6475-5}}. This chapter in Ruttman's history discusses Koufax's American, Jewish, baseball, and life experiences from youth to the present.\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{bbhof|koufax-sandy}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=117277|espn=23910|br=k/koufasa01|fangraphs=1007124|brm=koufax001san|retro=K/Pkoufs101}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/e463317c Sandy Koufax] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*{{IMDb name|id=1620721|name=Sandy Koufax}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050416222917/http://www.sportingnews.com/baseball/100/index-26.html sportingnews.com] ''The Sporting News'' Baseball's 100 Greatest Players (#26)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081229142835/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/ballplayers/player.php?name=Sandy_Koufax_1935 biography and career highlights] ''Baseball Library''\n*[https://www.facebook.com/groups/750642898334875/ Sandy Koufax Fan Page on Facebook]\n*[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:iHM34WqC2kgJ:www.chrisoleary.com/projects/baseball/Pitching/PitcherInjuryAnalysisProject/PhotographicAnalyses/PitcherAnalysis_SandyKoufax.pdf+sandy+koufax+injuries&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgucf1N4GwDenJ6COVnMIuE9nqv58vf9ryml-OR9DqkFrKbzxwnJdFCnOhwNWmBPQ0Bc6eiQiUBZ4KHzoxzWjhb8Z6fOBtsdykkC2o7bV7GA8z-1yP49ApEGybZBDUEjsouoqSh&sig=AHIEtbTUWv9OowOsXINTvkL5s__8IqSS1Q Analysis of Sandy Koufax's Pitching Motion and Injuries]\n*[http://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/94356/jewish/A-Pair-of-Tefillin-for-Sandy-Koufax.htm A Pair of Tefillin for Sandy Koufax] \u2013 article from [[Chabad.org]] about the impact of Koufax's decision not to pitch on Yom Kippur on the Jewish community\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-ach}}}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Don Drysdale]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Los Angeles Dodgers]] [[Opening Day]] <br /> [[Starting pitcher]]|years=1964}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Don Drysdale]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Earl Wilson (baseball)|Earl Wilson]]<br />[[Jack Kralick]]<br />[[Ken Johnson (right-handed pitcher)|Ken Johnson]]<br />[[Jim Maloney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Major League Baseball no-hitters|No-hitter pitcher]]|years=June 30, 1962<br />May 11, 1963<br />June 4, 1964<br />September 9, 1965}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bill Monbouquette]]<br />[[Don Nottebart]]<br />[[Jim Bunning]]<br />[[Dave Morehead]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bob Purkey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|Major League Player of the Month]]|years=June 1962}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Frank Howard (baseball)|Frank Howard]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Bunning]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Perfect game (baseball)|Perfect game pitcher]]|years=September 9, {{mlby|1965}}}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Catfish Hunter]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{1955 Brooklyn Dodgers}}\n{{1959 Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n{{1963 Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n{{1965 Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n{{MLBACT}}\n{{MLBATT}}\n{{NL MVPs}}\n{{MLB Combined Cy Young}}\n{{World Series MVPs}}\n{{Babe Ruth Award}}\n{{Hutch Award}}\n{{Hickok Belt}}\n{{The Sporting News MLB Player of the Year Award}}\n{{Sporting News NL Pitcher of the Year Award}}\n{{SI Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{APAthleteOTY}}\n{{MLB perfect games}}\n{{MLB Triple Crowns (pitchers)}}\n{{NL wins champions}}\n{{NL ERA champions}}\n{{NL strikeout champions}}\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers retired numbers}}\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{1972 Baseball HOF}}\n{{Baseball Hall of Fame members}}\n{{Major League Baseball on NBC}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koufax, Sandy}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats baseball players]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Columbia University School of General Studies alumni]]\n[[Category:Cy Young Award winners]]\n[[Category:International Jewish Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Jewish American baseball players]]\n[[Category:Jewish Major League Baseball players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers executives]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers who have pitched a perfect game]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players with retired numbers]]\n[[Category:World Series Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n[[Category:National Baseball Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National League ERA champions]]\n[[Category:National League Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n[[Category:National League Pitching Triple Crown winners]]\n[[Category:National League strikeout champions]]\n[[Category:National League wins champions]]\n[[Category:People from Hidden Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Borough Park, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Vero Beach, Florida]]\n[[Category:Lafayette High School (New York City) alumni]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:People from Rockville Centre, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Bensonhurst, Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Sandy Koufax\n|image=Sandy Koufax.jpg\n|caption=Koufax with the Los Angeles Dodgers, c. 1965\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Left\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1935|12|30}}\n|birth_place=[[Brooklyn, New York]]\n|debutleague=MLB\n|debutdate=June 24\n|debutyear=1955\n|debutteam=Brooklyn Dodgers\n|finalleague=MLB\n|finaldate=October 2\n|finalyear=1966\n|finalteam=Los Angeles Dodgers\n|statleague=MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=165\u201387\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=2.76\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=2,396\n|teams=\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Brooklyn / Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1966}})\n|highlights=\n* 7\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1961]]\u2013[[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1962]], [[1963 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1963]]\u2013[[1966 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1966]])\n* 4\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1955}}, {{wsy|1959}}, {{wsy|1963}}, {{wsy|1965}})\n* [[NL MVP]] (1963)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Cy Young Award]] (1963, 1965, 1966)\n* 2\u00d7 [[World Series MVP]] (1963, 1965)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball Triple Crown|Triple Crown]] (1963, 1965, 1966)\n* 3\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual wins leaders|MLB wins leader]] (1963, 1965, 1966)\n* 5\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual ERA leaders|NL ERA leader]] (1962\u20131966)\n* 4\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual strikeout leaders|MLB strikeout leader]] (1961, 1963, 1965, 1966)\n* Pitched a [[Sandy Koufax's perfect game|perfect game]] on September 9, 1965\n* Pitched four [[no-hitter]]s\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers#Retired numbers|Los Angeles Dodgers No. 32]] retired\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Time Team]]\n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate=[[1972 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|1972]]\n|hofvote=86.87% (first ballot)\n}}\n'''Sanford Koufax''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|f|\u00e6|k|s}}; born '''Sanford Braun'''; December 30, 1935) is an American former [[professional baseball]] left-handed [[pitcher]]. He pitched 12 seasons for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers|Brooklyn/Los Angeles Dodgers]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) from 1955 to 1966. Koufax, at age 36 in 1972, became the youngest player ever elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"kirby puckett\">{{cite web|title=Retired Numbers \u2013 Kirby Puckett|work=minnesota.twins.mlb.com|url=http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/min/history/puckett.jsp|access-date=February 10, 2007}}</ref> He has been hailed as one of the greatest pitchers in baseball history.\n\nKoufax's career peaked with a run of six outstanding years from {{mlby|1961}} to {{mlby|1966}}, before arthritis in his left elbow ended his career prematurely at age 30. He was an [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] for six seasons<ref name=\"baseballhall.org\">National Baseball Hall of Fame, \"six-time All-Star\" [http://www.baseballhall.org/hof/koufax-sandy] Retrieved April 15, 2015</ref> and was the  [[National League]]'s [[MLB Most Valuable Player award|Most Valuable Player]] in {{mlby|1963}}. He won three [[Cy Young Award]]s in 1963, {{mlby|1965}}, and 1966, by unanimous votes, making him the first three-time Cy Young winner in baseball history and the only one to win three times when one overall award was given for all of Major League Baseball instead of one award for each league. Koufax also won the NL [[Major League Baseball Triple Crown|Triple Crown]] for pitchers those same three years by leading the NL in [[win (baseball)|wins]], [[strikeout]]s, and [[earned run average]].<ref name=\"bbref-skoufax\">{{cite web|title=Sandy Koufax Statistics|work=www.baseball-reference.com|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/k/koufasa01.shtml|accessdate=February 14, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1963 Major League Leaders|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/ML_1963_t.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211223731/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/ML_1963_t.shtml|archivedate=February 11, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1965 Major League Leaders|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/ML_1965_t.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061215110435/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/ML_1965_t.shtml|archivedate=December 15, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1966 Major League Leaders|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/ML_1966_t.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071015041537/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/ML_1966_t.shtml|archivedate=October 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nKoufax was the first major league pitcher to pitch four [[no-hitter]]s and the eighth pitcher to pitch a [[Perfect game (baseball)|perfect game]] in baseball history. Despite his comparatively short career, Koufax's 2,396 career strikeouts ranked 7th in history as of his retirement, at the time trailing only [[Warren Spahn]] (2,583) among left-handers. Koufax, [[Trevor Hoffman]], [[Randy Johnson]], [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]], and [[Nolan Ryan]] are the only five pitchers elected to the Hall of Fame who had more strikeouts than innings pitched.\n\nKoufax is also remembered as one of the outstanding Jewish athletes in American sports. His decision not to pitch Game 1 of the [[1965 World Series]] because it fell on [[Yom Kippur]] garnered national attention as an example of conflict between professional pressures and personal beliefs.<ref name=\"yomkippur\">{{cite web|title=Yom Kippur and Sandy Koufax|work=JewishSports.com|first=Sandor|last=Solomvits|url=http://www.jewishsports.com/reflections/koufax_yom.htm|accessdate=August 2, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018193520/http://www.jewishsports.com/reflections/koufax_yom.htm|archivedate=October 18, 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:The Cincinnatian. 1954 baseball.png|thumb|left|270px|1954 University of Cincinnati baseball team photo with Sandy Koufax (top row, 5th from the left).]]\nKoufax was born in [[Brooklyn]], New York, to a [[Jewish]] family, and is Jewish himself and was raised in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn|Borough Park]].<ref name=JSR>{{cite journal |title=Big League Jews|journal=[[Jewish Sports Review]] |date=January\u2013February 2020 |volume=12 |issue=137 |page=19}}</ref><ref name=\"jewishvirtuallibrary.org\">{{cite web|title=Koufax Biography|work=jewishvirtuallibrary.org|first=Seymour|last=Brody|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/Koufax.html|accessdate=November 15, 2006}}</ref> His parents, Evelyn (n\u00e9e Lichtenstein) and Jack Braun, divorced when he was three years old. His mother was remarried when he was nine, to Irving Koufax.<ref name=\"hickocksports.com\">{{cite web|title=Koufax Biography|work=www.hickoksports.com|url=http://www.hickoksports.com/biograph/koufaxsandy.shtml|accessdate=November 15, 2006|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130111045314/http://www.hickoksports.com/biograph/koufaxsandy.shtml|archivedate=January 11, 2013}}</ref> Shortly after his mother's remarriage, the family moved to the [[Long Island]] suburb of [[Rockville Centre, New York|Rockville Centre]]. Before tenth grade, Koufax's family moved back to the [[Bensonhurst, Brooklyn|Bensonhurst]] section of Brooklyn.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 19\u201322.</ref>\n\nKoufax attended Brooklyn's [[Lafayette High School (New York City)|Lafayette High School]], where he was better known for [[basketball]] than for baseball. At the time, school sports were not available because New York's teachers were refusing to supervise extracurricular activities without monetary compensation. As an alternative, Koufax started playing basketball for the [[Edith and Carl Marks Jewish Community House of Bensonhurst]] local community center team. Eventually, Lafayette had a basketball team; Koufax became team captain in his senior year, and ranked second in his division in scoring, with 165 points in 10 games.<ref name=\"jewishvirtuallibrary.org\"/><ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 22\u201328; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 37\u201340.</ref> In 1951, at the age of 15, Koufax also joined a local youth baseball league known as the \"Ice Cream League\". He started out as a left-handed catcher before moving to first base. While playing first base for Lafayette High School's baseball team with teammate and friend [[Fred Wilpon]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandy Koufax could testify at trial|publisher=ESPN. Associated Press|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/story/_/id/7680912/sandy-koufax-bernard-madoff-new-york-mets-trial-witness-list|date=March 13, 2012|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref> he was spotted by Milt Laurie, the father of two Lafayette teammates and a baseball coach. Laurie recognized that Koufax might be able to pitch, and recruited the 17-year-old Koufax to pitch for the Coney Island Sports League's Parkviews.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 32\u201339.</ref>\n\nKoufax attended the [[University of Cincinnati]] and was a [[Walk-on (sports)|walk-on]] on the freshman basketball team, a complete unknown to coach [[Ed Jucker]].<ref name=\"hickocksports.com\"/> He later earned a partial scholarship. In spring 1954, he made the college baseball [[varsity team]].<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 43\u201344.</ref> In his only season, Koufax went 3\u20131 with a 2.81 [[earned run average|ERA]], 51 [[strikeout]]s and 30 [[base on balls|walks]] in 32 innings.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 50.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dyer|first=Mike|title=Sandy Koufax's season with UC Bearcats remembered|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=May 4, 2014|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/college/university-of-cincinnati/2014/04/30/sandy-koufax-season-with-uc-bearcats-remembered/8512237/|accessdate=June 20, 2016}}</ref> [[Bill Zinser]], a scout for the Brooklyn Dodgers, sent the Dodgers front office a glowing report that apparently was filed and forgotten.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 44\u201345.</ref>\n\nAfter trying out with the [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]] at the [[Polo Grounds]],<ref>[[#Gruver|Gruver]], p. 80.</ref> Koufax did the same for the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] at [[Forbes Field]].<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 56\u201357.</ref> During his Pirates tryout, Koufax's fastball broke the thumb of [[Sam Narron (catcher)|Sam Narron]], the team's bullpen coach. [[Branch Rickey]], then the [[general manager (baseball)|general manager]] of the Pirates, told his scout [[Clyde Sukeforth]] that Koufax had the \"greatest arm [he had] ever seen\".<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 54</ref> The Pirates, however, failed to offer Koufax a contract until after he was already committed to the Dodgers.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 70\u201374.</ref> Dodgers scout [[Al Campanis]] heard about Koufax from Jimmy Murphy, a part-time scout.<ref> Baseball Anecdotes by Daniel Okrent and Steve Wulf, Harper and Row Publishers, 1989</ref> After seeing Koufax pitch for Lafayette, Campanis invited him to an [[Ebbets Field]] tryout. With Dodgers manager [[Walter Alston]] and scouting director [[Fresco Thompson]] watching, Campanis assumed the hitter's stance while Koufax started throwing. Campanis later said, \"There are two times in my life the hair on my arms has stood up: The first time I saw the ceiling of the [[Sistine Chapel]] and the second time, I saw Sandy Koufax throw a fastball.\"<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 55</ref> The Dodgers signed Koufax for a $6,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|6000|1954|r=-3}}}} today) salary, with a $14,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|14000|1954|r=-3}}}} today) [[signing bonus]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Dalin|first=David G.|title=Why we can't forget Sandy Koufax|publisher=CBS News|date=September 27, 2011|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/why-we-cant-forget-sandy-koufax/|accessdate=January 12, 2017}}</ref> Koufax planned to use the money as tuition to finish his university education, if his baseball career failed.<ref>[[#Kahn|Kahn]], p. 95.</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Early years (1955\u20131960)===\n[[File:Portrait of the baseball player Sandy Koufax ca1950 (cropped).jpg|thumb|250px|Koufax]]\nBecause Koufax's signing bonus was greater than $4,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|4000|1954|r=-3}}}} today), he was known as a [[bonus rule|bonus baby]]. This forced the Dodgers to keep him on the major league roster for at least two years before he could be sent to the [[minor league baseball|minors]]. To make room for him, the Dodgers optioned their future [[Baseball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] manager, [[Tommy Lasorda]], to the [[Montreal Royals]] of the [[International League]]. Lasorda would later joke that it took Koufax to keep him off the Dodger pitching staff.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 42, 75\u201394.</ref>\n\nKoufax made his major league debut on June 24, {{mlby|1955}} against the [[1955 Milwaukee Braves season|Milwaukee Braves]], with the Dodgers trailing 7\u20131 in the fifth inning. [[Johnny Logan (baseball)|Johnny Logan]], the first batter Koufax faced, hit a bloop single. [[Eddie Mathews]] bunted, and Koufax threw the ball into center field. He then walked [[Hank Aaron]] on four pitches to load the bases, but struck out [[Bobby Thomson]] on a [[full count|3-2]] [[fastball]]\u2014an outcome Koufax later came to view as \"probably the worst thing that could have happened to me,\" leading, as it did, to five seasons spent \"trying to get out of trouble by throwing harder and harder and harder.\"<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 95\u201397.</ref>\n\n[[File:Cincinnati Redlegs at Brooklyn Dodgers 1955-08-27 (ticket).jpg|125px|right|thumb|upright|A ticket from the game where Koufax earned his first career win.]]\nKoufax's first start was on July 6.<ref>{{cite news|last=Biederman|first=Lester J.|title=Koufax Recalls His Wild Start At Forbes Field|work=Pittsburgh Press|date=May 16, 1966|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149182939/|page=35|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> He lasted only {{fraction|4|2|3}} innings, giving up eight walks.<ref name=\"Leavy74\">[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 74.</ref> He did not start again for almost two months, but on August 27, Koufax threw a two-hit, 7\u20130 [[complete game]] [[shutouts in baseball|shutout]] against the [[1955 Cincinnati Redlegs season|Cincinnati Reds]] for his first major league win.<ref name=\"Leavy74\"/><ref>[[#McNeil|McNeil]], p. 182.</ref> Koufax threw {{frac|41|2|3}} innings in 12 appearances that season, striking out 30 batters and walking 28. He had two wins in 1955, which were both shutouts.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 74\u201375.</ref>\n\nDuring the fall, he enrolled in the [[Columbia University School of General Studies]], which offered night classes in architecture. The [[1955 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Dodgers]] won the [[1955 World Series]] for the first title in franchise history, but Koufax did not appear in the series. After the final out of Game Seven, Koufax drove to Columbia to attend class.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 3, 105\u2013107.</ref>\n\nThe year 1956 was not very different from 1955 for Koufax. Despite the blazing speed of his fastball, Koufax continued to struggle with his control.<ref>{{harvp|Faber|2010|p=57}}</ref> He saw little work, pitching only 58.7 innings with a 4.91 ERA, 29 walks and 30 strikeouts. When Koufax allowed baserunners, he was rarely permitted to finish the inning. Teammate [[Joe Pignatano]] said that, as soon as Koufax threw a couple of balls in a row, Alston would signal for a replacement to start warming up in the bullpen. [[Jackie Robinson]], in his final season, clashed with Alston on Koufax's usage. Robinson saw that Koufax was talented and had flashes of brilliance, and objected to Koufax being benched for weeks at a time.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 85\u201386.</ref>\n\nTo prepare for the {{mlby|1957}} season, the [[1957 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Dodgers]] sent Koufax to [[Puerto Rico]] to play winter ball. On May 15, the restriction on sending Koufax down to the minors was lifted. Alston gave him a chance to justify his place on the major league roster by giving him the next day's start. Facing the [[1957 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] at [[Wrigley Field]], Koufax struck out 13 while pitching his first complete game in almost two years. For the first time in his career, he was in the starting rotation, but only for two weeks. Despite winning three of his next five with a 2.90 ERA, Koufax did not get another start for 45 days. In that start, he struck out 11 in seven innings, but got a no-decision. On September 29, Koufax became the last man to pitch for the Brooklyn Dodgers before their move to Los Angeles, by throwing an inning of relief in the final game of the season.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 117\u2013124; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 87\u201390.</ref>\n\nOver the next three seasons, Koufax was in and out of the Dodger starting rotation due to injuries. In 1958, he began 7\u20133, but sprained his ankle in a collision at first base, finishing the season at 11\u201311 and leading the NL in wild pitches. In June 1959, Koufax set the record for a night game with 16 strikeouts. On August 31, 1959, he surpassed his career high with 18 strikeouts, setting the NL record and tying [[Bob Feller]]'s major league record for strikeouts in one game.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 125\u2013138; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 90\u201392; {{cite web|title=Box score and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/B08310LAN1959.htm|accessdate=February 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn {{Baseball year|1959}}, the Dodgers won a close pennant race against the [[1959 Milwaukee Braves season|Braves]] and the [[1959 San Francisco Giants season|Giants]], then beat the [[1959 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]] in the [[1959 World Series|World Series]]. Koufax pitched two perfect relief innings in the Series opener, though they came after the Dodgers were already behind 11\u20130. Alston gave him the start in the fifth game, at the [[Los Angeles Coliseum]] in front of 92,706 fans. Koufax allowed only one run in seven innings, but lost the 1\u20130 game when [[Nellie Fox]] scored on a double play. Returning to Chicago, the Dodgers won the sixth game and the Series.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 139\u2013141; {{cite web|title=Box score and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/B10060LAN1959.htm|accessdate=February 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn early {{Baseball year|1960}}, Koufax asked Dodgers GM [[Buzzie Bavasi]] to trade him because he was not getting enough playing time. By the end of [[1960 Los Angeles Dodgers season|1960]], after going 8\u201313, Koufax was thinking about quitting baseball to devote himself to an [[electronics]] business that he had invested in. After the last game of the season, he threw his gloves and spikes into the trash. Nobe Kawano, the clubhouse supervisor, retrieved the equipment to return to Koufax the following year (or to somebody else if Koufax did not return to play).<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 142\u2013147; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 93\u201395.</ref>\n\n===Domination (1961\u20131964)===\n\n====1961 season====\n[[File:Sandy Koufax 1961.png|thumb|180px|Koufax in 1961.]]\nKoufax tried one more year of baseball and showed up for the 1961 season in better condition than he had in previous years. Years later he recalled, \"That winter was when I really started working out. I started running more. I decided I was really going to find out how good I can be.\"<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 101.</ref> During spring training, Dodger scout Kenny Myers discovered a hitch in Koufax's windup: he would rear back so far that his vision was obstructed and he could not see the target.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 102.</ref>\n\nA day later, Koufax was pitching for the \"B team\" in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]]. Teammate [[Ed Palmquist]] missed the flight, so Koufax was told he would need to pitch at least seven innings. In the first inning, Koufax walked the bases loaded on 12 straight pitches. Catcher [[Norm Sherry]] advised Koufax to throw slightly less hard in order to improve his control. The advice worked, as Koufax struck out the side, going on to pitch seven no-hit innings.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 153\u2013155; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 102\u2013103.</ref>\n\nIt was the beginning of Koufax's breakout season. Posting an 18\u201313 record for the Dodgers in 1961, Koufax led the league with 269 strikeouts, breaking [[Christy Mathewson]]'s 58-year-old NL mark of 267.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 157\u2013159; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 115\u2013116.</ref> Koufax was selected as an All-Star for the first time and made two [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] appearances; MLB held two All-Star games from 1959 through 1962.<ref name=\"sportsdatallc.com\">Sportsdata: Midsummer Classics: Celebrating MLB's All-Star Game, 1959\u20131962, \"all players who were named to the AL or NL roster were credited one appearance per season.\" Retrieved April 15, 2015 [http://www.sportsdatallc.com/2012/07/09/midsummer-classics-celebrating-mlbs-all-star-game]</ref> He faced only one batter in the 9th inning in the first game, giving up a hit to [[Al Kaline]] and he pitched two scoreless innings in the second game.<ref>{{cite web|title=First game box score and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/B07110NLS1961.htm|accessdate=February 17, 2007}} {{cite web|title=Second game box score and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/B07310ALS1961.htm|accessdate=February 17, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====1962 season====\nIn {{Baseball year|1962}}, the Dodgers moved from the Los Angeles Coliseum, which had a 250-foot left field line, to pitcher-friendly [[Dodger Stadium]]. The new park had a large foul territory and a comparatively poor hitting background. Koufax was an immediate beneficiary of the change, lowering his home ERA from 4.29 to 1.75.<ref>[[#James|James]], p. 233; [[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 127\u2013128; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 116.</ref> On June 30 against the expansion [[New York Mets]], Koufax threw his first no-hitter. In the first inning of that game, Koufax struck out three batters on nine pitches to become the sixth National League pitcher and the 11th pitcher in Major League history to accomplish a [[pitchers who struck out three batters on nine pitches|nine-pitch/three-strikeout half-inning]], also called an immaculate inning. With the no-hitter, a 4-2 record, 73 strikeouts, and a 1.23 ERA for June, he was named [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award]].<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 167\u2013169; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 119; {{cite web|title=Player of the Month Award|publisher=Baseball Almanac|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/awards/player_of_the_month_award.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"9pitch9strike\">{{cite web|title=9-Pitches, 9-Strikes, Side Retired|publisher=Baseball Almanac|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/feats/feats17.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007}}</ref> It would be the only time in his career he earned this distinction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Major League Baseball Players of the Month|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/mlb-players-of-the-month.shtml|accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:1962 Bell Brand Sandy Koufax.jpg|thumb|right|1962 [[Bell Brand Snack Foods|Bell Brand]] Sandy Koufax]]\nKoufax had his strong season despite an injured pitching hand. While batting in April, Koufax had been jammed by a pitch from [[Earl Francis]]. A numbness developed in Koufax's index finger on his left hand, and the finger became cold and white. Koufax was pitching better than ever, however, so he ignored the problem, hoping that the condition would clear up. By July, though, his entire hand was becoming numb and he was unable to complete some games. In a start in Cincinnati, his finger split open after one inning. A vascular specialist determined that Koufax had a crushed artery in his palm. Ten days of experimental medicine successfully reopened the artery. Koufax finally was able to pitch again in September, when the team was locked in a tight pennant race with the Giants. But after the long layoff, Koufax was ineffective in three appearances as the Giants caught the Dodgers at the end of the regular season, forcing a three-game playoff.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 165\u2013176; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 120\u2013121.</ref>\n\nThe night before the National League playoffs began, Manager [[Walter Alston]] asked Koufax if he could start the first game the next day. With an overworked pitching staff, there was no one else, as [[Don Drysdale]] and [[Johnny Podres]] had pitched the prior two days. Koufax obliged. Koufax later said, \"I had nothing at all.\" He was knocked out in the second inning, after giving up home runs to future Hall of Famer [[Willie Mays]] and [[Jim Davenport]]. After winning the second game of the series, the Dodgers blew a 4\u20132 lead in the ninth inning of the deciding third game, losing the pennant.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 176\u2013177; [[#Neyer|Neyer]], pp. 111\u2013118.</ref>\n\n====1963 season====\nIn 1963, Major League Baseball expanded the [[strike zone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/articles/strike_zone_rules_history.shtml|title=The Strike Zone: A Chronological Examination of the Official Rules by Baseball Almanac|publisher=Baseball-almanac.com|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> Compared to the previous season, National League walks fell 13 percent, strikeouts increased six percent, the league batting average fell from .261 to .245, and runs scored declined 15 percent.<ref>{{cite web|title=1962 National League Team Statistics and Standings|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1962.shtml|accessdate=June 20, 2010}}{{cite web|title=1963 National League Team Statistics and Standings|website=Baseball-Reference| url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/1963.shtml|accessdate=June 20, 2010}}</ref> Koufax, who had reduced his walks allowed per nine innings to 3.4 in 1961 and 2.8 in 1962, reduced his walk rate further to 1.7 in 1963, which ranked fifth in the league.<ref name=\"bbref-skoufax\"/> The top pitchers of the era \u2013 [[Don Drysdale]], [[Juan Marichal]], [[Jim Bunning]], [[Bob Gibson]], [[Warren Spahn]], and above all Koufax \u2013 significantly reduced the walks-given-up-to-batters-faced ratio for 1963, and subsequent years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/|title=Baseball Encyclopedia of MLB Players|website=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 11, Koufax [[No-hitter|no-hit]] the [[San Francisco Giants]] 8-0, besting future Hall of Fame pitcher [[Juan Marichal]]\u2014himself a no-hit pitcher a month later, on June 15. Koufax carried a [[Perfect game (baseball)|perfect game]] into the eighth inning against the powerful [[1963 San Francisco Giants season|Giants]] lineup, including future Hall of Famers Willie Mays, [[Willie McCovey]], and [[Orlando Cepeda]]. He walked [[Ed Bailey]] on a 3-and-2 pitch in the eighth, and pinch-hitter McCovey on four pitches in the ninth, before closing out the game.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 181\u2013183; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 122\u2013123.</ref> As the Dodgers won the pennant, Koufax won the pitchers' [[Major League Baseball Triple Crown|Triple Crown]], leading the league in wins (25), strikeouts (306) and ERA (1.88).<ref>[[#The Baseball Chronicle|''The Baseball Chronicle'']], p. 344.</ref> Koufax threw 11 shutouts, setting a new post-1900 record for shutouts by a left-handed pitcher that stands to this day (the previous record of 10 shutouts had been held by [[Carl Hubbell]] for 30 years). Only [[Bob Gibson]], a right-hander, has thrown more shutouts (13) since, and that was in 1968,<ref>{{cite web|title=Single-Season Leaders & Records for Shutouts|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/SHO_season.shtml|accessdate=November 1, 2017}}</ref> \"the year of the pitcher.\"<ref>[[#Gruver|Gruver]], p. 234.</ref>\n\nKoufax won the NL [[MLB Most Valuable Player award|MVP Award]] and the [[Hickok Belt]], and was the first-ever unanimous selection for the [[Cy Young Award]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1963 National League Statistics and Awards|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1963.shtml|accessdate=February 18, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206210245/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL_1963.shtml|archivedate=February 6, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"hickokbelt\">{{cite web|title=The Hickok Belt |publisher=HickokSports.com |url=http://www.hickoksports.com/history/hickbelt.shtml |accessdate=February 18, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20020223060736/http://www.hickoksports.com/history/hickbelt.shtml |archivedate=February 23, 2002 }}</ref>\n\nFacing the [[1963 New York Yankees season|Yankees]] in the [[1963 World Series]], Koufax beat [[Whitey Ford]] 5\u20132 in Game 1 and struck out 15 batters \u2013 including the first 5, breaking [[Carl Erskine]]'s decade-old record of 14 (Gibson would break Koufax's record by striking out 17 [[1968 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]] in the [[1968 World Series]] opener). After seeing Koufax's Game 1 performance, [[Yogi Berra]] said, \"I can see how he won 25 games. What I don't understand is how he lost five,\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandy Koufax Biography|work=ESPN SportsCentury|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/biography/s/Koufax_Sandy.html|accessdate=May 24, 2005}}</ref> to which [[Maury Wills]] responded, \"He didn't. We lost them for him.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Ronald N. Neff, www.thornwalker.com|url=http://www.sobran.com/columns/2007/070329.htm|title=Joe Sobran \u2013 My Other Sandy (ASCII version)|publisher=Sobran.com|date=March 29, 2007|accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref> In Game 4, Koufax completed the Dodgers' series sweep with a 2\u20131 victory over Ford, clinching the [[World Series MVP Award|Series MVP Award]] for his performance.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 184\u2013216; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 132\u2013143; {{cite web|title=World Series MVP Award|publisher=Baseball Almanac|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/awards/aw_mvpw.shtml|accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1963 World Series box scores and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1963/YPS_1963.htm|accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====1964 season====\nKoufax's {{mlby|1964}} season started with great expectations. On April 18, he struck out three batters on nine pitches in the third inning of a 3\u20130 loss to the [[1964 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati Reds]], becoming the only National League pitcher to have two [[pitchers who struck out three batters on nine pitches|nine-pitch/three-strikeout half-innings]].<ref name=\"9pitch9strike\"/> On April 22, however, \"he felt something let go in his arm.\" Koufax ended up getting three [[cortisone]] shots for his sore elbow, and missed three starts.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 150.</ref>\n\nOn June 4, playing at [[Connie Mack Stadium]] against the [[1964 Philadelphia Phillies season|Phillies]], Koufax [[base on balls|walked]] [[Dick Allen|Richie Allen]] on a very close full-count pitch in the fourth inning. Allen, who was thrown out trying to steal second, was the only Phillie to reach base that day. With his third no-hitter in three years, Koufax became only the second pitcher of the modern era (after [[Bob Feller]]) to pitch three no-hitters.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 219\u2013221; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 151\u2013153.</ref>\n\nKoufax jammed his pitching arm in August while diving back to second base to beat a pick-off throw. He managed to pitch and win two more games. However, the morning after his 19th win, a shutout in which he struck out 13 batters, he could not straighten his arm. He was diagnosed by Dodgers' team physician [[Robert Kerlan]] with traumatic [[arthritis]]. With the Dodgers out of the pennant race, the book was closed on Koufax and his 19\u20135 record.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 222\u2013228; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 155\u2013157.</ref>\n\n===Playing in pain (1965\u201366)===\n\n====1965 season====\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Koufax mag.jpg|thumb|Sandy Koufax on the cover of ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', March 4, 1963]] -->\nThe 1965 season brought more obstacles for Koufax. On March 31, the morning after pitching a complete [[spring training]] game, Koufax awoke to find that his entire left arm was [[bruise|black and blue]] from [[hemorrhage|hemorrhaging]]. Koufax returned to Los Angeles to consult with Kerlan, who advised Koufax that he would be lucky to be able to pitch once a week. Kerlan also told Koufax that he would eventually lose full use of his arm. Koufax agreed not to throw at all between games\u2014a resolution that lasted only one start. To get himself through the games he pitched in, Koufax resorted to Empirin with [[codeine]] for the pain, which he took every night and sometimes during the fifth inning. He also took [[Phenylbutazone|Butazolidin]] for inflammation, applied [[capsaicin]]-based Capsolin ointment (called \"atomic balm\" by baseball players) before each game, and soaked his arm in a tub of ice afterwards.<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 228\u2013239; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 157\u2013160.</ref>\n\nDespite the constant pain in his pitching elbow, Koufax pitched 335\u2154 innings and led the [[1965 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]] to another pennant. He finished the year by winning his second pitchers' Triple Crown, leading the league in wins (26), ERA (2.04) and strikeouts (382; the highest modern day total at the time. [[Nolan Ryan]] struck out 383 batters in {{Baseball year|1973}}). Koufax captured his second unanimous Cy Young Award. Koufax held batters to 5.79 hits per nine innings, and allowed the fewest base runners per 9 innings in any season ever: 7.83, breaking his own record (set two years earlier) of 7.96. Koufax had 11-game winning streaks in both 1964 and 1965.<ref name=\"bbref-skoufax\"/><ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 234\u2013240; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 160; {{cite web|title=Single-Season Leaders for Strikeouts|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/SO_p_season.shtml|accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====Perfection====\n{{Main|Sandy Koufax's perfect game}}\n\nOn September 9, 1965, Koufax became the sixth pitcher of the modern era, and eighth overall, to throw a perfect game, the first by a left-hander since 1880.<ref>{{cite web|last=Eagle |first=Ed |title=All-time perfect games in MLB history |publisher=Major League Baseball |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/perfect-game/c-265862286 |date=June 13, 2018 |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"perfect\">{{cite web|last=Clair |first=Michael |title=On this day 49 years ago, Sandy Koufax threw a perfect game ... in one hour and 43 minutes |publisher=Major League Baseball |url=https://www.mlb.com/cut4/49-years-ago-sandy-koufax-threw-perfect-game-one-hour-43-minutes/c-93862524 |date=September 9, 2014 |accessdate=December 31, 2018}}</ref> The game was Koufax's fourth no-hitter,<ref name=\"perfect\"/> setting a Major League record (subsequently broken by [[Nolan Ryan]] in 1981).<ref>{{cite web|last=Coffey|first=Alex|title=Domination in the Dome: Nolan Ryan Throws His Fifth No-Hitter|publisher=National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|url=https://baseballhall.org/discover-more/stories/inside-pitch/nolan-ryan-fifth-no-hitter|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Koufax struck out 14 batters, at the time the most recorded in a perfect game (tied by [[Matt Cain]] in 2012). The game also featured a quality performance by the opposing pitcher, [[Bob Hendley]] of the [[1965 Chicago Cubs season|Cubs]]. Hendley pitched a one-hitter and allowed only two batters to reach base. Both pitchers had no-hitters intact until the seventh inning.\n\nThis remains the only nine-inning major league game where the teams combined for just one hit. The game's only run, scored by the Dodgers, was [[earned run|unearned]].<ref name=\"baseballlibrary\">{{cite web|title=Sandy Koufax |work=www.baseballlibrary.com |url=http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/K/Koufax_Sandy.stm |accessdate=February 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070202141624/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/K/Koufax_Sandy.stm |archivedate=February 2, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Attiyeh|first=Mike|title=The five best pitching duels ever|publisher=BaseballGuru.com|url=http://baseballguru.com/attiyeh/analysismikeattiyeh04.html|accessdate=February 18, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070214143847/http://baseballguru.com/attiyeh/analysismikeattiyeh04.html <!--Added by H3llBot-->|archivedate=February 14, 2007}} {{cite web|title=Box score and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1965/B09090LAN1965.htm|accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref> The Dodger run was scored without a recorded at bat when [[Lou Johnson]] walked, reached second on a sacrifice bunt, stole third, and scored when the throw to get him out at third went wild.\n\n====World Series and Yom Kippur====\nKoufax garnered headlines by declining to pitch Game 1 of the [[1965 World Series|World Series]] because of his observance of the Jewish religious holiday of [[Yom Kippur]]. \nThis decision garnered national attention as an example of conflict between professional pressures and personal religious beliefs.<ref name=\"yomkippur\"/> [[Don Drysdale]] pitched the opener, but was hit hard by the [[1965 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]].\n\nIn Game 2, Koufax pitched six innings, giving up two runs, and the Twins won the Game 5\u20131 and took an early 2\u20130 lead in the series. The Dodgers fought back in Games 3 and 4, with wins by [[Claude Osteen]] and Drysdale. With the Series tied at 2 to 2, Koufax pitched a complete game shutout in Game 5 for a 3\u20132 Dodgers lead as the Series returned to [[Metropolitan Stadium|Minnesota's Metropolitan Stadium]] for Game 6. The Twins won Game 6 to force a seventh game. Starting Game 7 on just two days of rest, Koufax pitched through fatigue and arthritic pain. Despite giving up on his curveball early in the game after failing to throw strikes with it in the first two innings and pitching the rest of the game relying almost entirely on fastballs, Koufax threw a three-hit shutout to clinch the Series. The performance earned him his second World Series MVP award. Koufax also won the [[Hickok Belt]] a second time, the first time anyone had won the belt more than once. He was awarded ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' magazine's [[Sportsman of the Year]] award.<ref name=\"bbref-skoufax\"/><ref name=\"hickokbelt\"/><ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], pp. 256\u2013268; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 169\u2013195; {{cite web|title=1965 World Series box scores and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet|url=http://retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1965/YPS_1965.htm|accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\n====1966 season====\n\n=====Holdout=====\nBefore the 1966 season began, Koufax and Drysdale met separately with Dodger GM [[Buzzie Bavasi]] to negotiate their contracts for the upcoming year. After Koufax's meeting, he met Drysdale for dinner and complained that Bavasi was using Drysdale against him in the negotiations, asking, \"How come you want that much when Drysdale only wants this much?\"<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 205</ref> Drysdale responded that Bavasi did the same thing with him, using Koufax against him. Drysdale's first wife, Ginger Drysdale, suggested that they negotiate together to get what they wanted. They demanded $1 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|1|1966|r=1}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}), divided equally over the next three years, or $167,000 (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|0.167|1966|r=2}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}) each for each of the next three seasons. Both players were represented by an entertainment lawyer, J. William Hayes, which was unusual during an era when players were not represented by agents.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 200\u2013207.</ref><ref name=STT>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,835304,00.html|title=Sic Transit Tradition|accessdate=April 30, 2008|date=April 8, 1966 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> At the time, Willie Mays was [[Major League Baseball]]'s highest paid player at $125,000 (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|0.125|1966|r=2}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}) per year and multi-year contracts were very unusual.<ref name=DP>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,842547,00.html|title=Double Play|accessdate=April 30, 2008|date=March 25, 1966|publisher=[[Time, Inc.]]|work=Time}}</ref>\n\nKoufax and Drysdale did not report to spring training in February. Instead, they both signed to appear in the movie ''[[Warning Shot (1967 film)|Warning Shot]]'', starring [[David Janssen]]. Drysdale was to play a TV commentator and Koufax a [[detective]]. Meanwhile, the Dodgers waged a [[public relations]] battle against them. After four weeks, Koufax gave Drysdale the go-ahead to negotiate new deals for both of them. Koufax ended up getting $125,000 and Drysdale $110,000 (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|0.110|1966|r=2}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}). They rejoined the team in the last week of spring training.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 207\u2013210.</ref>\nIn April 1966, Kerlan told Koufax it was time to retire and that his arm could not take another season. Koufax kept Kerlan's advice to himself and went out every fourth day to pitch. He ended up pitching 323 innings, a 27\u20139 record, and a 1.73 ERA. Since then, no left-hander has had more wins, nor a lower ERA, in a season (Phillies pitcher [[Steve Carlton]] did match the 27-win mark in 1972). In the final game of the regular season, the Dodgers had to beat the Phillies to win the pennant. In the second game of a doubleheader, Koufax faced [[Jim Bunning]] for the second time that season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAN/LAN196607270.shtml|title=July 27 box score|website=Baseball-Reference.com|date=July 27, 1966|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> in a match-up between perfect game winners. Koufax, on two days rest, pitched a complete game, winning 6\u20133 to clinch the pennant.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 222\u2013236.</ref> He started 41 games (for the second year in a row); only two left-handers started as many games in any season over the ensuing years through 2018.\n\n=====Season=====\nThe [[1966 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]] went on to face the [[1966 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]] in the [[1966 World Series|World Series]], and Game 2 marked Koufax's third start in eight days. He pitched well enough\u2014Baltimore first baseman [[Boog Powell]] told Koufax's biographer, [[Jane Leavy]], \"He might have been hurtin' but he was bringin'\"\u2014but three errors by Dodger center fielder [[Willie Davis (baseball)|Willie Davis]] in the fifth inning produced three unearned runs. Baltimore's twenty-year-old [[Jim Palmer]] pitched a four-hitter and the Orioles won 6\u20130.<ref name=bmitst>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=MpsRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DekDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7186%2C2382682 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=Baltimore makes it two straight as Dodgers defense comes apart |date=October 7, 1966 |page=18}}</ref> Alston lifted Koufax at the end of the sixth {{nowrap|inning,<ref name=bmitst/><ref>{{cite web|title=Box score and play by play|publisher=Retrosheet |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1966/B10060LAN1966.htm |accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref>}} with the idea of getting him extra rest before a potential fifth game. It never happened; the Dodgers were swept in four games, not scoring a single run in the last {{nowrap|three.<ref name=ibifs>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8t5XAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DekDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7410%2C3710325 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |title=It's Baltimore in four straight |date=October 10, 1966 |page=8}}</ref>}} Less than six weeks later, Koufax announced his retirement due to his arthritic condition on Friday, {{nowrap|November 18, 1966.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 236\u2013239</ref><ref name=eltomu>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=V8xYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AekDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7417%2C995655 |work=Spokesman-Review |location=(Spokane, Washington) |agency=Associated Press |last=Myers |first=Bob |title=Elbow too much - Sandy Koufax quitting baseball  |date=November 19, 1966 |page=10}}</ref>}}\n\n===Career overall===\nIn his 12-season career, Koufax had a 165\u201387 record with a 2.76 ERA, 2,396 strikeouts, 137 complete games, and 40 shutouts. He was the first pitcher to average fewer than seven [[hit (baseball)|hits]] allowed per nine [[innings pitched]] in his career (6.79) and to strike out more than nine batters (9.28) per nine innings pitched in his career.<ref>{{cite web|title=No Hitter Records|publisher=Baseball Almanac|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/recbooks/rb_noh1.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007}} {{cite web|title=Progressive Leaders for Hits Allowed/9IP|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/Hp9_progress.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011214851/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/Hp9_progress.shtml|archivedate=October 11, 2007}} {{cite web|title=Progressive Leaders for Strikeouts/9IP|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/SOp9_progress.shtml|accessdate=February 17, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001145047/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/SOp9_progress.shtml|archivedate=October 1, 2007}}</ref> He also became the 2nd pitcher in baseball history to have two games with 18 or more strikeouts, and the first to have eight games with 15 or more strikeouts. In his last ten seasons, from 1957 to 1966, batters hit .203 against Koufax, with a .271 [[on-base percentage]] and a .315 [[slugging percentage|slugging average]].<ref>The play-by-play data from which these averages were calculated are available starting in 1957. See {{cite web|title=Career Leaders   & Records for Earned Run Average|website=Baseball-Reference|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/earned_run_avg_career.shtml|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nKoufax's postseason record is impressive: a 4\u20133 won-lost record with a 0.95 earned run average, in four World Series. He is on the very short list of pitchers who retired with more career strikeouts than innings pitched. Koufax was selected as an All-Star for six consecutive seasons<ref name=\"baseballhall.org\"/> and made seven out of eight All-Star Game appearances those seasons (he was not selected for 2nd All-Star Game in 1962).<ref name=\"sportsdatallc.com\"/> He pitched 6{{frac|1|3}} innings in four All-Star games including being the starting pitcher for 3 innings in the 1966 All-Star Game.\n\nKoufax was the first pitcher to win multiple Cy Young Awards, as well as the first pitcher to win a Cy Young Award by a unanimous vote. He is also the only pitcher to win three Cy Young Awards in the era in which the award was presented to one pitcher across the board, rather than one in each major league, and one of three Dodgers pitchers to win the one-across-the-board Cy Young Award. (The others were [[Don Newcombe]], the first Cy Young winner in 1956, and [[Don Drysdale]] in 1962.) Each of Koufax's three Cy Young Awards were by unanimous vote.<ref name=\"bbref-skoufax\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=MVP and Cy Young Awards|work=www.baseball-reference.com|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/mvp_cya.shtml|accessdate=February 14, 2007}}</ref> Koufax and Juan Marichal are the only two pitchers in the post-war era (1946-date) to have more than one 25-win season, with each pitcher recording three.\n\nAmong NL pitchers with at least 2,000 innings pitched who have debuted since {{Baseball year|1913}} and have already retired, he has the highest career winning percentage (.655) and had the lowest career ERA (2.76) until surpassed by [[Tom Seaver]], whose NL career mark is 2.73. While Seaver ended his career with an overall career ERA of 2.86, this included three seasons in the American League. Seaver passed Koufax's mark in 1974 when he ended the season with more than 2,000 NL innings and an ERA of 2.47. Among retired pitchers, Koufax is currently second on the list of overall career ERA in the live-ball era, surpassed only by Whitey Ford (2.75).\n\nThrough 2010, among Jewish pitchers, he was first all-time in career strikeouts (ahead of [[Ken Holtzman]]), second in wins (behind Holtzman) and ERA (behind [[Barney Pelty]]), and seventh in games pitched (behind [[Alan Levine]]) among Jewish major league baseball players.<ref name=\"JML\">{{cite web|title=Career Pitching Leaders|url=http://www.jewishmajorleaguers.org/|work=Career Leaders|publisher=Jewish Major Leaguers|accessdate=February 10, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826042258/http://jewishmajorleaguers.org/|archive-date=August 26, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Pitching style==\n{{Quote box|width=20em|bgcolor=|align=right|quote=\"I knew every pitch he was going to throw and still I couldn't hit him.\"<ref>[[#Koufax and Linn|Koufax and Linn]], p. 153; [[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 24.</ref>\n | source= \u2014[[Willie Mays]]}}\n\nWhereas many pitchers throw with a three-quarter or sidearm motion, Koufax threw with a pronounced over-the-top arm action. This may have increased his [[velocity]], but reduced the lateral movement on his pitches, especially movement away from left-handed hitters. Most of his velocity came from his strong legs and back, combined with a high kicking wind-up and long forward stretch toward the plate. Throughout his career, Koufax relied mostly on two pitches.<ref name=\"pitches\"/> His [[four-seam fastball]] gave batters the impression of rising as it approached them, due to underspin.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 7\u20138, 79.</ref> It not only appeared to move very late but also might move two or three distinct times. His overhand [[curveball]], spun with the middle finger, dropped vertically 12 to 24&nbsp;inches due to his arm action. [[Rob Neyer]] called it the best curve of all time.<ref>{{harvp|Neyer|James|2004|p=34}}</ref> He also occasionally threw a [[changeup]] and a [[forkball]].<ref name=\"pitches\"/>\n\nAt the beginning of his career, Koufax worked with coaches to eliminate his tendency to \"tip\" pitches (i.e., reveal which pitch was coming due to variations in his wind-up). Late in his career, and especially as his arm problems continued, this variation\u2014usually in the position he held his hands at the top of the wind-up\u2014became even more pronounced. Good hitters could often predict what pitch was coming, but were still unable to hit it.\n\n==Post-playing career==\n{{MLBBioRet\n|Image  = LAret32.PNG\n|Name   = Sandy Koufax\n|Number = 32\n|Team   = Los Angeles Dodgers\n|Year   = 1972\n|}}\nIn 1967, Koufax signed a 10-year contract with [[Major League Baseball on NBC|NBC]] for US$1 million (equivalent to ${{Inflation|US|1|1967|r=1}}&nbsp;million in {{Inflation/year|US}}) to be a broadcaster on the ''[[Major League Baseball Game of the Week|Saturday Game of the Week]]''. He quit after six years, just prior to the start of the {{Baseball year|1973}} season.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], p. 251.</ref><ref name=\"espn65series\">{{cite web|last=Schwartz|first=Larry|title=ESPN Classic \u2013 Koufax dominating in '65 Series|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/biography/s/koufaxsandyadd.html|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref>\n\nKoufax married Anne Widmark, daughter of movie star [[Richard Widmark]], in 1969; the couple divorced in 1982. His second marriage, to Kimberly Francis, a personal trainer, lasted from 1985 to 1998.<ref name=\"espn65series\"/> Koufax is currently married to Jane Purucker Clarke. He has no biological children.\n\nIn his first year of eligibility in {{mlby|1972}}, Koufax was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame, just weeks after his 36th birthday. His election made him the Hall's youngest member ever elected, five months younger than [[Lou Gehrig]] upon his election in 1939, though because the 1972 induction ceremony was nearly eight months after the election, Koufax's age at induction was slightly older than Gehrig's, making Gehrig the youngest player ever inducted.<ref name=\"kirby puckett\" /> On June 4 of that same year, Koufax's uniform number 32 was [[Los Angeles Dodgers#Retired numbers|retired]] alongside those of Dodger greats [[Roy Campanella]] (39) and Jackie Robinson (42).<ref>{{cite web|title=Dodgers Retired Numbers|work=MLB.com|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/la/history/retired_numbers.jsp|accessdate= February 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Dodgers hired Koufax to be a minor league pitching coach in {{mlby|1979}}. He resigned in {{mlby|1990}}, saying he was not earning his keep, but most observers blamed it on his uneasy relationship with manager Tommy Lasorda.<ref>[[#Leavy|Leavy]], pp. 255\u2013258.</ref>  Koufax returned to the Dodger organization in {{mlby|2004}} when the Dodgers were sold to [[Frank McCourt (executive)|Frank McCourt]].<ref name=\"baseballlibrary\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Koufax returns to Dodgertown|work=Addict Baseball and Football Forum|url=http://www.addictsports.com/baseball/archive/index.php/t-33921.html|accessdate=February 15, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041228044405/http://www.addictsports.com/baseball/archive/index.php/t-33921.html|archivedate=December 28, 2004}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sandy Koufax 2014.jpg|thumb|230px|Koufax at the 2014 [[BBWAA]] dinner]] \nIn {{mlby|1999}}, ''[[The Sporting News]]'' placed Koufax at number 26 on its list of \"Baseball's 100 Greatest Players\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Sporting News Selects Baseball's 100 Greatest Players|journal=The Sporting News|date=April 26, 1999|volume=223|issue=17|page=16}}</ref> That same year, he was named as one of the 30 players on the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]. Although he rarely makes public appearances, he went to [[Turner Field]] in [[Atlanta]] for the introduction ceremony before Game 2 of the [[1999 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The All-Century Team|work=mlb.mlb.com|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/history/mlb_history_moreinfo.jsp|accessdate=February 15, 2007}} {{cite news|title=Koufax makes appearance at World Series|work=CNN/SI|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/1999/postseason/world_series/news/1999/10/24/koufax_appearance_ap/|accessdate=February 15, 2007|date=October 24, 1999|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006102051/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/1999/postseason/world_series/news/1999/10/24/koufax_appearance_ap|archivedate=October 6, 2008}}</ref> Koufax threw out a ceremonial first pitch at opening day 2008 at Dodger Stadium, to help commemorate the Dodgers' 50th Anniversary in Los Angeles.\n\nKoufax was the final player chosen in the inaugural [[Israel Baseball League]] draft in April 2007. Koufax, 71, was picked by the [[Modi'in Miracle]]. \"His selection is a tribute to the esteem with which he is held by everyone associated with this league\", said [[Art Shamsky]], who managed the Miracle. \"It's been 41 years between starts for him. If he's rested and ready to take the mound again, we want him on our team.\" Koufax declined to join the Miracle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://humbug.baseballtoaster.com/archives/642563.html|title=Baseball Toaster: Humbug Journal : He'll be working on 14,875 days rest|publisher=Humbug.baseballtoaster.com|date=April 24, 2007|accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Lloyd de Vries|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/04/27/sportsline/main2735685.shtml|title=Koufax Drafted By Israeli Baseball Team|publisher=CBS News|date=April 27, 2007|accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\nCurrently, Koufax serves as a member of the advisory board of the [[Baseball Assistance Team]], a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization dedicated to helping former Major League, Minor League, and Negro League players through financial and medical difficulties.\n\nOn January 23, 2013 the Dodgers hired Koufax as a Special Advisor to team Chairman [[Mark Walter]]. Koufax worked with the pitchers during spring training and will consult during the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://losangeles.dodgers.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130122&content_id=41089434&vkey=news_la&c_id=la|title=Dodgers to be joined by Koufax at Spring Training|publisher=Los Angeles Dodgers}}</ref> On April 1, 2013, Koufax threw out the first pitch during ceremonies at Dodger Stadium.\n\nOn July 14, 2015, before the [[2015 MLB All-Star Game]] in Cincinnati, Koufax was introduced as one of the four best living players (as selected by the fans of major league baseball), along with [[Willie Mays]], [[Hank Aaron]] and [[Johnny Bench]].  He threw the ceremonial first pitch to Bench from in front of the base of the mound.\n\nOn November 1, 2017, before Game 7 of the [[2017 World Series]] between the Dodgers and [[Houston Astros]] at [[Dodger Stadium]], Koufax threw the ceremonial first pitch along with [[Don Newcombe]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Gartland|first=Dan|title=Watch: Dodgers Bring Out Pitching Legends Sandy Koufax and Don Newcombe for Game 7 First Pitch|magazine=Sports Illustrated|date=November 1, 2017|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2017/11/02/world-series-game-7-first-pitch-sandy-koufax-don-newcombe-video|accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==White House recognition==\n[[File:JAHM 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Sandy Koufax (center of first row) at first White House reception for [[Jewish American Heritage Month]], May 27, 2010. At Koufax's right are Vice President [[Joe Biden]] and First Lady [[Michelle Obama]]]]\nOn May 27, 2010, Koufax was included among a group of prominent Jewish Americans at the first White House reception in honor of [[Jewish American Heritage Month]]. [[U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]] during welcome remarks in a reminiscence of Koufax's decision not to play on the Jewish holy day of Yom Kippur said that the two had \"something in common.\"  President Obama continued: \"He can't pitch on [[Yom Kippur]]. I can't pitch.\"<ref name=\"JAHM\">{{cite web|last=Knoller|first=Mark|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20006236-503544.html|title=\"Obama Honors Jewish Americans at White House Reception\", May 27, 2010|publisher=Cbsnews.com|date=May 27, 2010|accessdate=January 31, 2011}}</ref> The President also directly acknowledged the high esteem in which Koufax is held:\n\n:\"This is a pretty fancy ... pretty distinguished group\", he said of the invited guests, which included members of the House and Senate, two justices of the Supreme Court, Olympic athletes, entrepreneurs, Rabbinical scholars, \"and Sandy Koufax\". The mention of his name brought the biggest cheer at the event.<ref name=\"JAHM\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Sandy Koufax's career statistics<ref name=\"bbref-skoufax\"/>\n!W !! L !! ERA !! G !! GS !! CG !! SHO !! SV !! IP !! H !! R !! ER !! HR !! BB !! SO !! HBP !! WP !! BF !! WHIP !! ERA+\n!WAR\n|-\n|165 || 87 || 2.76 || 399 || 314 || 137 || 40 || 9 || 2,324.1 || 1,754 || 806 || 713 || 204 || 817 || 2,396 || 18 || 87 || 9,497 || 1.106 || 131\n|53.1\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Baseball|Judaism}}\n{{Div col}}\n*[[List of baseball players who went directly to Major League Baseball]]\n*[[Bonus rule]]\n*[[Major League Baseball Triple Crown]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball annual ERA leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball annual strikeout leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball annual wins leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball single-game strikeout leaders]]\n*[[List of Major League Baseball pitchers who have struck out three batters on nine pitches]]\n*