{"title_page": "Polabian language", "text_new": "{{Expand Russian|\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0431\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Polabian\n|states=[[Poland]], [[Germany]]\n|extinct=18th century\n|familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=[[Balto-Slavic languages|Balto-Slavic]]\n|fam3=[[Slavic languages|Slavic]]\n|fam4=[[West Slavic languages|West Slavic]]\n|fam5=[[Lechitic languages|Lechitic]]\n|map=Polabian Slavs.png\n|mapcaption=Grey: Former settlement area of the Polabian Slavs. Green: Uninhabited forest areas. Darker shade just indicates higher elevation. The map already shows the [[Saxons|Saxon (Sasov\u00e9)]] invasion into the [[Veleti]]c/[[Slavs|Slavic]] territory of the [[Volcae|Volci (Volcae)]], [[Chatti|Chaci (Chatti)]] and [[Cherusci|Chru\u015bci (Cherusci)]] called [[Hercynian Forest|Perkunia (Aryan), Orkynia (Greek) or Hercynia (Latin)]].\n|iso3=pox\n|glotto=pola1255\n|glottorefname=Polabian\n|linglist=pox\n|lingua=53-AAA-bc\n}}\n\nThe '''Polabian language''' is an [[extinct language|extinct]] [[West Slavic languages|West Slavic]] language that was spoken by the [[Polabian Slavs]] ({{lang-de|Wenden}}) in present-day northeastern [[Germany]] around the [[Elbe]] (''\u0141aba/Laba/Labe'' in Slavic) river, from which derives its name (''po Labe'' - [traveling] on Elbe or [living] up to Elbe). It was spoken approximately until the rise to power of [[Prussia]] in mid-18th century, when it was superseded by [[Low German]].\n\nBy the 18th century, [[Lechitic languages|Lechitic]] Polabian was in some respects markedly different from other [[Slavic languages]], most notably in having a strong [[German language|German]] influence. It was close to [[Pomeranian language|Pomeranian]] and [[Kashubian language|Kashubian]], and is attested only in a handful of manuscripts, dictionaries and various writings from the 17th and 18th centuries.\n\n==History==\nAbout 2800 Polabian words are known; of prose writings, only a few prayers, one wedding song and a few folktales survive. Immediately before the language became extinct, several people started to collect phrases and compile wordlists, and were engaged with folklore of the [[Polabian Slavs]], but only one of them appears to have been a native speaker of Polabian (himself leaving only 13 pages of linguistically relevant material from a 310-page manuscript).<ref>{{harvtxt|Kapovi\u0107|2008|p=109}}</ref> The last native speaker of Polabian, a woman, died in 1756, and the last person who spoke limited Polabian died in 1825.\n\nThe most important monument of the language is the so-called ''Vocabularium Venedicum'' (1679\u20131719) by Christian Hennig.\n\nThe language left many traces to this day in toponymy; for example, [[Wustrow, Lower Saxony|Wustrow]] (way to the island or place on the island), [[L\u00fcchow|Ljauch\u00f3w (L\u00fcchow)]], [[Luckau (Wendland)|\u0141uk\u00f3w (Luckau)]], [[Sagard]], [[Gartow]], [[Krakow am See|Krakow]] (resembling [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Krakov (Rakovn\u00edk District)|Krakov]]\u2026) etc. Polabian language is also a likely origin of the name [[wikt:Berlin|Berlin]], from the Polabian stem ''berl-''/''birl-'' (swamp).\n\n==Grammar==\n\n===Phonology===\nFor Polabian the following segments are reconstructable:<ref>Cited after {{harvtxt|Kazimierz |1993|p=799}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Oral non-reduced monophthongs\n|{{IPA|i&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;y&nbsp;}}\n|\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;u}}\n|-\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;e&nbsp;}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u025b&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0153&nbsp;}}\n|\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0254&nbsp;}}\n|-\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;a&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0252&nbsp;}}\n|}\n\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Reduced\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0259&nbsp;}}\n|-\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0250&nbsp;}}\n|}\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Diphthongs\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;ai&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u0252i&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;oi&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;au&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u0252u&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|}\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Nasal\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u00e3&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u0254\u0303&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Polabian consonant segments\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\"|\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[dental consonant|Dental]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[palatal consonant|Post-<br />palatal]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[plosive consonant|Plosives]]\n| align=center | {{IPA|p}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|p\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|t}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|t\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|k}}\n|-\n| align=center | {{IPA|b}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|b\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|d}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|d\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|\u0261}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[affricate consonant|Affricates]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|t\u0361s}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|t\u0361s\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|d\u0361z}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|d\u0361z\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[fricative consonant|Fricatives]]\n| align=center | {{IPA|f}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|s}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|\u0283}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|s\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|x\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|x}}\n|-\n| align=center | {{IPA|v}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|v\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|z}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|z\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" |[[Nasal stop|Nasals]]\n| align=center | {{IPA|m}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|m\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|n}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|n\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" |[[lateral consonant|Laterals]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|l}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|l\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" |[[trill consonant|Trills]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|r}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|r\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[Semi-vowel]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|j}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|}\n\n==Example of Polabian==\nThe ''[[Lord's Prayer]]'' in Polabian and related [[Lechitic languages]], compared to [[Old Church Slavonic]], German and English:<ref>Polabian version quoted after [http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/didact/idg/slav/polabbs.htm#EN3 TITUS project]</ref> Germanic loanwords, which are comparatively rare in the other [[West Slavic languages]], are highlighted in '''bold''' (loanwords in Germanic versions are highlighted as well).\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|'''Drav\u00e9nopolabski''' (Draw\u00e4nopolabian):\n\n:N\u00f4se '''Wader,'''\n:ta toy gis wa Nebisg\u00e1y,\n:Sjungta '''woarda''' Tyg\u00ed Geima,\n:Tia '''R\u00eek''' '''komaj''',\n:Tia Willia \u015b\u010diny\u00f4t,\n:kok wa Nebisg\u00e1y,\n:t\u00f4k kak no Zime. \n:N\u00f4si wisedanneisna Stgeiba doy n\u00e2m d\u00e2ns,\n:un wittedoy n\u00e2m n\u00f4se Ggr\u00each,\n:kak moy wittedoyime n\u00f4sem Gr\u00easmarim. \n:Ni '''bringoy''' n\u00f4s ka '''War\u015bik\u00f3nye,'''\n:tay '''l\u00f6\u015bo\u00e1y''' n\u00f4s wit wis\u00f3kak \u0160audak.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|'''Po\u0142abski:''' (Eastern Polabian):\n\n:Aita Nos,\n:t\u00e2 toi jis w\u00e2 nebesai,\n:Sj\u0119ty '''wordoj''' Tyji jaim\u0105,\n:Tyji '''Rik''' '''komaj''',\n:Tyja wy\u013ea mo s\u0105 \u0165y\u0144ot,\n:kok w\u00e2 nebesai,\n:tok no zemi,\n:nos\u0119 wisedanesn\u0119 s\u0165aib\u0119 doj nam d\u00e2ns,\n:a wyt\u00e2doj nam nose greche,\n:kok moi wyt\u00e2dojeme nosim gresnarem. \n:Ni '''bringoj''' nos w\u00e2 '''Warsykong\u0119,'''\n:toi '''losoj''' nos wyt wisokag \u0161audag.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Upper Sorbian language|Hornioserb\u0161\u0107ina (Upper Sorbian)]]:\n\n:W\u00f3t\u010de na\u0161,\n:ki\u017e sy w niebiesach.\n:Swie\u0107 so Twoje mieno.\n:P\u0159i\u0144d\u017a Twoje Kral\u011bstwo.\n:Sta\u0144 so Twoja wola,\n:ka\u017e na niebju,\n:tak na zemi.\n:W\u0161\u011bdny chl\u011bb na\u0161 daj nam d\u017aens.\n:Wodaj nam na\u0161e winy,\n:jako my wodawamy na\u0161im winikam; \n:A niewjed\u017a nas do spytowanja,\n:ale wum\u00f3\u017e nas wot z\u0142eho.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Kashubian language|Kashubian]]:\n\n:\u00d2jcze nasz,\n:jaczi jes w niebie,\n:niech s\u00e3 swi\u00e3cy Tw\u00f2je miono,\n:niech przi\u0144dze Tw\u00f2je kr\u00f3lestw\u00f2,\n:niech mdze Tw\u00f2ja w\u00f2l\u00f4\n:jakno w niebie\n:tak t\u00e9\u017c na zemi.\n:Chleba naj\u00e9g\u00f2 p\u00f2wszedn\u00e9g\u00f2 d\u00f4j n\u00f3m dzys\u00f4\n:i \u00f2dp\u00f9sc\u00eb n\u00f3m naje win\u00eb,\n:jak i m\u00eb \u00f2dp\u00f9szcziw\u00f3me naszim winowajc\u00f3m; \n:A nie dop\u00f9sc\u00eb na nas p\u00f2k\u00f9szeni\u00f4,\n:ale nas zbawi \u00f2de z\u0142\u00e9g\u00f2.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Polish language|Polish]]:\n\n:Ojcze nasz,\n:kt\u00f3ry\u015b jest w niebie,\n:\u015bwi\u0119\u0107 si\u0119 imi\u0119 Twoje,\n:przyjd\u017a kr\u00f3lestwo Twoje,\n:b\u0105d\u017a wola Twoja\n:jako w niebie\n:tak i na ziemi.\n:Chleba naszego powszedniego daj nam dzisiaj;\n:i odpu\u015b\u0107 nam nasze winy,\n:jako i my odpuszczamy naszym winowajcom;\n:i nie w\u00f3d\u017a nas na pokuszenie,\n:ale nas zbaw ode z\u0142ego.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Old Church Slavonic|Old Slavic (transliteration)]]:\n\n:Ot\u012d\u010de na\u0161\u012d,\n:I\u017ee jesi na nebes\u011bch\u016d. \n:Da sv\u0119tit\u016d s\u0119 im\u0119 Tvoje,\n:da pridet\u016d c\u011bsar'\u012dstvije Tvoje,\n:da b\u01ebdet\u016d volja Tvoja\n:jako na nebesi\n:i na zeml'i.\n:Chl\u011bb\u016d na\u0161\u012d nas\u01eb\u0161t\u012dnyi da\u017ed\u012d nam\u016d d\u012dn\u012ds\u012d; \n:i ot\u016dpusti nam\u016d dl\u016dgy na\u0161\u0119,\n:jako i my ot\u016dpu\u0161tajem\u016d dl\u016d\u017e\u012dnikom\u016d na\u0161im\u016d;\n:i ne v\u016dvedi nas\u016d v\u016d isku\u0161enije,\n:n\u016d izbavi ny ot\u016d neprijazni.\n: Amin\u012d.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[German language|German, 8th century]]:\n\n:'''Fater''' uns\u00ear,\n:'''thu''' '''pist''' '''in''' himile,\n:uu\u00eehi '''namun''' d\u00eenan,\n:qhueme '''r\u00eehhi''' d\u00een,\n:uuerde '''uuillo''' diin, \n:s\u00f4 '''in''' himile \n:s\u00f4sa '''in''' '''erdu'''.\n:Prooth uns\u00ear emezzihic kip uns hiutu, \n:'''obl\u00e2z''' uns '''sculdi''' uns\u00earo,\n:s\u00f4 uuir '''obl\u00e2z\u00eam''' uns '''sculd\u00eek\u00eam''', \n:enti '''ni''' unsih firleiti '''in''' khorunka,\n:\u00fbzzer l\u00f4si unsih fona '''ubile'''. \n: '''Amen'''.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[German language|German, 20th century]]:\n\n:'''Vater''' unser,\n:der '''Du''' '''bist''' '''im''' Himmel,\n:geheiligt werde Dein '''Name''';\n:zu uns komme Dein '''Reich''';\n:Dein '''Wille''' geschehe,\n:wie '''im''' Himmel,\n:also auch auf '''Erden'''!\n:Unser t\u00e4gliches Brot gib uns heute;\n:und vergib uns unsere '''Schuld''',\n:wie auch wir vergeben unsern '''Schuldigern''';\n:und f\u00fchre uns '''nicht''' '''in''' '''Versuchung''',\n:sondern erl\u00f6se uns von dem '''\u00dcbel'''.\n: '''Amen'''.\n|}\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[English language|English]]:<ref>[http://www.englishtexts.org/praying.pdf Praying Together] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201315/http://www.englishtexts.org/praying.pdf |date=2013-10-29}}</ref>\n\n:Our '''Father'''\n:who art '''in''' heaven,\n:hallowed '''be''' '''thy''' '''name'''.\n:'''Thy''' kingdom come,\n:'''thy''' '''will''' '''be''' done\n:on '''earth'''\n:as it '''is''' '''in''' heaven.\n:Give us '''this''' '''day''' our '''daily''' bread, and\n:forgive us our '''trespasses''' (or \"debts\"; ''cf.'' German use of feminine singular ''Schuld'', \"debt\"/\"guilt\")\n:as we forgive '''those''' who '''trespass''' against us (or \"our debtors\"; German ''Schuldiger[e]n'', however, refers only to perpetrators of wrongdoing, with dative plural of \"debtors\" instead being ''Schuld[e]ner[e]n''),\n:and lead us '''not''' '''into''' '''temptation'''\n:but '''deliver''' us from '''evil''' (or \"the Evil One\").\n: '''Amen'''.\n|}{{clear left}}\n\n==See also==\n{{incubator|pox}}\n{{OldWikisource|Wenska rec}}\n{{Commons category|Polabian language}}\n*[[Wends]]\n*[[Polabians (tribe)]]\n*[[Veleti]] \n*[[House of Griffins]]\n*[[Slavic Native Faith]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{citation |first=Reinhold |last=Olesch |authorlink=Reinhold Olesch |title=Jezik polapskih Drevana: Stanje i zadaci istra\u017eivanja |language=Serbo-Croatian |url=http://suvlin.ffzg.hr/index.php/suvlin/article/view/387/298 |format=PDF |year=1977 |journal=[[Suvremena lingvistika]] |volume=15 |location=Zagreb |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506101919/http://suvlin.ffzg.hr/index.php/suvlin/article/view/387/298 |archive-date=2009-05-06 |df= }}\n*{{citation |first=Mate |last=Kapovi\u0107 |authorlink=Mate Kapovi\u0107 |title=Uvod u indoeuropsku lingvistiku |location=[[Zagreb]] |publisher=[[Matica hrvatska]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-953-150-847-6 |language=Serbo-Croatian}}\n*{{citation |first=Ewa |last=Rzetelska-Feleszko |authorlink=Ewa Rzetelska-Feleszko |chapter=Polabisch |title=Enzyklop\u00e4die des Europ\u00e4ischen Ostens |language=German |url=http://www.uni-klu.ac.at/eeo/Polabisch.pdf |format=PDF |year=2002 |location=Klagenfurt |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927005136/http://www.uni-klu.ac.at/eeo/Polabisch.pdf |archive-date=2007-09-27 |df= }}\n* {{citation |last=Pola\u0144ski |first=Kazimierz |editor=Bernard Comrie and Greville G. Corbett |title=The Slavonic languages |chapter=Polabian |publisher=Routledge |year=1993 |location=London & New York |isbn=978-0-415-28078-5}}\n*''S\u0142ownik etymologiczny j\u0119zyka Drzewian po\u0142abskich'', Part 1: ed. Tadeusz Lehr-Sp\u0142awi\u0144ski & Kazimierz Pola\u0144ski, Wroc\u0142aw, 1962, from Part 2 on: ed. K. Pola\u0144ski, Wroc\u0142aw, 1971\u2013\n*Kazimierz Pola\u0144ski & Janusz Sehnert: ''Polabian-English Dictionary''. The Hague: Mouton 1967\n\n{{Slavic languages}}\n{{Pomeranian history}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polabian Language}}\n[[Category:Lechitic languages]]\n[[Category:Extinct Slavic languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Germany]]\n[[Category:Languages extinct in the 18th century]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Russian|\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0431\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Polabian\n|states=[[Poland]], [[Germany]]\n|extinct=18th century\n|familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=[[Balto-Slavic languages|Balto-Slavic]]\n|fam3=[[Slavic languages|Slavic]]\n|fam4=[[West Slavic languages|West Slavic]]\n|fam5=[[Lechitic languages|Lechitic]]\n|map=Polabian Slavs.png\n|mapcaption=Grey: Former settlement area of the Polabian Slavs. Green: Uninhabited forest areas. Darker shade just indicates higher elevation. The map already shows the [[Saxons|Saxon (Sasov\u00e9)]] invasion into the [[Veleti]]c/[[Slavs|Slavic]] territory of the [[Volcae|Volci (Volcae)]], [[Chatti|Chaci (Chatti)]] and [[Cherusci|Chru\u015bci (Cherusci)]] called [[Hercynian Forest|Perkunia (Aryan), Orkynia (Greek) or Hercynia (Latin)]].\n|iso3=pox\n|glotto=pola1255\n|glottorefname=Polabian\n|linglist=pox\n|lingua=53-AAA-bc\n}}\n\nThe '''Polabian language''' is an [[extinct language|extinct]] [[West Slavic languages|West Slavic]] language that was spoken by the [[Polabian Slavs]] ({{lang-de|Wenden}}) in present-day northeastern [[Germany]] around the [[Elbe]] (''\u0141aba/Laba/Labe'' in Slavic) river, from which derives its name (''po Labe'' - [traveling] on Elbe or [living] up to Elbe). It was spoken approximately until the rise to power of [[Prussia]] in mid-18th century, when it was superseded by [[Low German]].\n\nBy the 18th century, [[Lechitic languages|Lechitic]] Polabian was in some respects markedly different from other [[Slavic languages]], most notably in having a strong [[German language|German]] influence. It was close to [[Pomeranian language|Pomeranian]] and [[Kashubian language|Kashubian]], and is attested only in a handful of manuscripts, dictionaries and various writings from the 17th and 18th centuries.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Egtvedpigen.jpg|thumb|260px|[[Treetrunk coffin]] of the [[Egtved Girl]], apparently a young noble women of the [[Arya]] of [[Speyergau|Spyrgowa]] (related to the owners of the [[Golden Hat of Schifferstadt]]) of the early [[Eneti]]/[[Veleti]] (around 1400 BCE) at the [[National Museum of Denmark]].]]\n[[Image:Nachbildung Goldschtz ausgestellt Foto B. Klitzke.jpg|right|thumb|260px|Display of the replica of the [[Aryan]]-[[Saka|Scythian]] [[Eberswalde Hoard|hoard found at Fin\u00f3w (Eberswalde)]].]]\nAbout 2800 Polabian words are known; of prose writings, only a few prayers, one wedding song and a few folktales survive. Immediately before the language became extinct, several people started to collect phrases and compile wordlists, and were engaged with folklore of the [[Polabian Slavs]], but only one of them appears to have been a native speaker of Polabian (himself leaving only 13 pages of linguistically relevant material from a 310-page manuscript).<ref>{{harvtxt|Kapovi\u0107|2008|p=109}}</ref> The last native speaker of Polabian, a woman, died in 1756, and the last person who spoke limited Polabian died in 1825.\n\nThe most important monument of the language is the so-called ''Vocabularium Venedicum'' (1679\u20131719) by Christian Hennig.\n\nThe language left many traces to this day in toponymy; for example, [[Wustrow, Lower Saxony|Wustrow]] (way to the island or place on the island), [[L\u00fcchow|Ljauch\u00f3w (L\u00fcchow)]], [[Luckau (Wendland)|\u0141uk\u00f3w (Luckau)]], compare [[Lucknow|Luknow (Lucknow)]] in [[\u0100ry\u0101varta]], [[Sagard]], [[Gartow]], [[Krakow am See|Krakow]] (resembling [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Krakov (Rakovn\u00edk District)|Krakov]]\u2026) etc. Polabian language is also a likely origin of the name [[wikt:Berlin|Berlin]], from the Polabian stem ''berl-''/''birl-'' (swamp).\n\n==Grammar==\n\n===Phonology===\nFor Polabian the following segments are reconstructable:<ref>Cited after {{harvtxt|Kazimierz |1993|p=799}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Oral non-reduced monophthongs\n|{{IPA|i&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;y&nbsp;}}\n|\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;u}}\n|-\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;e&nbsp;}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u025b&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0153&nbsp;}}\n|\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0254&nbsp;}}\n|-\n|\n|\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;a&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0252&nbsp;}}\n|}\n\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Reduced\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0259&nbsp;}}\n|-\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;\u0250&nbsp;}}\n|}\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Diphthongs\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;ai&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u0252i&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;oi&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;au&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u0252u&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|}\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Nasal\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u00e3&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|{{IPA|&nbsp;&nbsp;\u0254\u0303&nbsp;&nbsp;}}\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Polabian consonant segments\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\"|\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Labial consonant|Labial]]\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[dental consonant|Dental]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[palatal consonant|Post-<br />palatal]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[plosive consonant|Plosives]]\n| align=center | {{IPA|p}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|p\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|t}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|t\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|k}}\n|-\n| align=center | {{IPA|b}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|b\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|d}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|d\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|\u0261}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\"|[[affricate consonant|Affricates]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|t\u0361s}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|t\u0361s\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|d\u0361z}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|d\u0361z\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"2\" |[[fricative consonant|Fricatives]]\n| align=center | {{IPA|f}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|s}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|\u0283}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|s\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|x\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|x}}\n|-\n| align=center | {{IPA|v}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|v\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|z}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|z\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" |[[Nasal stop|Nasals]]\n| align=center | {{IPA|m}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|m\u02b2}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|n}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|n\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" |[[lateral consonant|Laterals]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|l}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|l\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"1\" |[[trill consonant|Trills]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|r}}\n| align=center | {{IPA|r\u02b2}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|-\n!colspan=\"1\"|[[Semi-vowel]]\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n| align=center | {{IPA|j}}\n| align=center |\n| align=center |\n|}\n\n==Example of Polabian==\nThe ''[[Lord's Prayer]]'' in Polabian and related [[Lechitic languages]], compared to [[Old Church Slavonic]], German and English:<ref>Polabian version quoted after [http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/didact/idg/slav/polabbs.htm#EN3 TITUS project]</ref> Germanic loanwords, which are comparatively rare in the other [[West Slavic languages]], are highlighted in '''bold''' (loanwords in Germanic versions are highlighted as well).\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|'''Drav\u00e9nopolabski''' (Draw\u00e4nopolabian):\n\n:N\u00f4se '''Wader,'''\n:ta toy gis wa Nebisg\u00e1y,\n:Sjungta '''woarda''' Tyg\u00ed Geima,\n:Tia '''R\u00eek''' '''komaj''',\n:Tia Willia \u015b\u010diny\u00f4t,\n:kok wa Nebisg\u00e1y,\n:t\u00f4k kak no Zime. \n:N\u00f4si wisedanneisna Stgeiba doy n\u00e2m d\u00e2ns,\n:un wittedoy n\u00e2m n\u00f4se Ggr\u00each,\n:kak moy wittedoyime n\u00f4sem Gr\u00easmarim. \n:Ni '''bringoy''' n\u00f4s ka '''War\u015bik\u00f3nye,'''\n:tay '''l\u00f6\u015bo\u00e1y''' n\u00f4s wit wis\u00f3kak \u0160audak.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|'''Po\u0142abski:''' (Eastern Polabian):\n\n:Aita Nos,\n:t\u00e2 toi jis w\u00e2 nebesai,\n:Sj\u0119ty '''wordoj''' Tyji jaim\u0105,\n:Tyji '''Rik''' '''komaj''',\n:Tyja wy\u013ea mo s\u0105 \u0165y\u0144ot,\n:kok w\u00e2 nebesai,\n:tok no zemi,\n:nos\u0119 wisedanesn\u0119 s\u0165aib\u0119 doj nam d\u00e2ns,\n:a wyt\u00e2doj nam nose greche,\n:kok moi wyt\u00e2dojeme nosim gresnarem. \n:Ni '''bringoj''' nos w\u00e2 '''Warsykong\u0119,'''\n:toi '''losoj''' nos wyt wisokag \u0161audag.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Upper Sorbian language|Hornioserb\u0161\u0107ina (Upper Sorbian)]]:\n\n:W\u00f3t\u010de na\u0161,\n:ki\u017e sy w niebiesach.\n:Swie\u0107 so Twoje mieno.\n:P\u0159i\u0144d\u017a Twoje Kral\u011bstwo.\n:Sta\u0144 so Twoja wola,\n:ka\u017e na niebju,\n:tak na zemi.\n:W\u0161\u011bdny chl\u011bb na\u0161 daj nam d\u017aens.\n:Wodaj nam na\u0161e winy,\n:jako my wodawamy na\u0161im winikam; \n:A niewjed\u017a nas do spytowanja,\n:ale wum\u00f3\u017e nas wot z\u0142eho.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Kashubian language|Kashubian]]:\n\n:\u00d2jcze nasz,\n:jaczi jes w niebie,\n:niech s\u00e3 swi\u00e3cy Tw\u00f2je miono,\n:niech przi\u0144dze Tw\u00f2je kr\u00f3lestw\u00f2,\n:niech mdze Tw\u00f2ja w\u00f2l\u00f4\n:jakno w niebie\n:tak t\u00e9\u017c na zemi.\n:Chleba naj\u00e9g\u00f2 p\u00f2wszedn\u00e9g\u00f2 d\u00f4j n\u00f3m dzys\u00f4\n:i \u00f2dp\u00f9sc\u00eb n\u00f3m naje win\u00eb,\n:jak i m\u00eb \u00f2dp\u00f9szcziw\u00f3me naszim winowajc\u00f3m; \n:A nie dop\u00f9sc\u00eb na nas p\u00f2k\u00f9szeni\u00f4,\n:ale nas zbawi \u00f2de z\u0142\u00e9g\u00f2.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Polish language|Polish]]:\n\n:Ojcze nasz,\n:kt\u00f3ry\u015b jest w niebie,\n:\u015bwi\u0119\u0107 si\u0119 imi\u0119 Twoje,\n:przyjd\u017a kr\u00f3lestwo Twoje,\n:b\u0105d\u017a wola Twoja\n:jako w niebie\n:tak i na ziemi.\n:Chleba naszego powszedniego daj nam dzisiaj;\n:i odpu\u015b\u0107 nam nasze winy,\n:jako i my odpuszczamy naszym winowajcom;\n:i nie w\u00f3d\u017a nas na pokuszenie,\n:ale nas zbaw ode z\u0142ego.\n: Amen.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[Old Church Slavonic|Old Slavic (transliteration)]]:\n\n:Ot\u012d\u010de na\u0161\u012d,\n:I\u017ee jesi na nebes\u011bch\u016d. \n:Da sv\u0119tit\u016d s\u0119 im\u0119 Tvoje,\n:da pridet\u016d c\u011bsar'\u012dstvije Tvoje,\n:da b\u01ebdet\u016d volja Tvoja\n:jako na nebesi\n:i na zeml'i.\n:Chl\u011bb\u016d na\u0161\u012d nas\u01eb\u0161t\u012dnyi da\u017ed\u012d nam\u016d d\u012dn\u012ds\u012d; \n:i ot\u016dpusti nam\u016d dl\u016dgy na\u0161\u0119,\n:jako i my ot\u016dpu\u0161tajem\u016d dl\u016d\u017e\u012dnikom\u016d na\u0161im\u016d;\n:i ne v\u016dvedi nas\u016d v\u016d isku\u0161enije,\n:n\u016d izbavi ny ot\u016d neprijazni.\n: Amin\u012d.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[German language|German, 8th century]]:\n\n:'''Fater''' uns\u00ear,\n:'''thu''' '''pist''' '''in''' himile,\n:uu\u00eehi '''namun''' d\u00eenan,\n:qhueme '''r\u00eehhi''' d\u00een,\n:uuerde '''uuillo''' diin, \n:s\u00f4 '''in''' himile \n:s\u00f4sa '''in''' '''erdu'''.\n:Prooth uns\u00ear emezzihic kip uns hiutu, \n:'''obl\u00e2z''' uns '''sculdi''' uns\u00earo,\n:s\u00f4 uuir '''obl\u00e2z\u00eam''' uns '''sculd\u00eek\u00eam''', \n:enti '''ni''' unsih firleiti '''in''' khorunka,\n:\u00fbzzer l\u00f4si unsih fona '''ubile'''. \n: '''Amen'''.\n|}\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[German language|German, 20th century]]:\n\n:'''Vater''' unser,\n:der '''Du''' '''bist''' '''im''' Himmel,\n:geheiligt werde Dein '''Name''';\n:zu uns komme Dein '''Reich''';\n:Dein '''Wille''' geschehe,\n:wie '''im''' Himmel,\n:also auch auf '''Erden'''!\n:Unser t\u00e4gliches Brot gib uns heute;\n:und vergib uns unsere '''Schuld''',\n:wie auch wir vergeben unsern '''Schuldigern''';\n:und f\u00fchre uns '''nicht''' '''in''' '''Versuchung''',\n:sondern erl\u00f6se uns von dem '''\u00dcbel'''.\n: '''Amen'''.\n|}\n\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:left; margin:1em\"\n|[[English language|English]]:<ref>[http://www.englishtexts.org/praying.pdf Praying Together] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201315/http://www.englishtexts.org/praying.pdf |date=2013-10-29}}</ref>\n\n:Our '''Father'''\n:who art '''in''' heaven,\n:hallowed '''be''' '''thy''' '''name'''.\n:'''Thy''' kingdom come,\n:'''thy''' '''will''' '''be''' done\n:on '''earth'''\n:as it '''is''' '''in''' heaven.\n:Give us '''this''' '''day''' our '''daily''' bread, and\n:forgive us our '''trespasses''' (or \"debts\"; ''cf.'' German use of feminine singular ''Schuld'', \"debt\"/\"guilt\")\n:as we forgive '''those''' who '''trespass''' against us (or \"our debtors\"; German ''Schuldiger[e]n'', however, refers only to perpetrators of wrongdoing, with dative plural of \"debtors\" instead being ''Schuld[e]ner[e]n''),\n:and lead us '''not''' '''into''' '''temptation'''\n:but '''deliver''' us from '''evil''' (or \"the Evil One\").\n: '''Amen'''.\n|}{{clear left}}\n\n==See also==\n{{incubator|pox}}\n{{OldWikisource|Wenska rec}}\n{{Commons category|Polabian language}}\n*[[Wends]]\n*[[Polabians (tribe)]]\n*[[Veleti]] \n*[[House of Griffins]]\n*[[Slavic Native Faith]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{citation |first=Reinhold |last=Olesch |authorlink=Reinhold Olesch |title=Jezik polapskih Drevana: Stanje i zadaci istra\u017eivanja |language=Serbo-Croatian |url=http://suvlin.ffzg.hr/index.php/suvlin/article/view/387/298 |format=PDF |year=1977 |journal=[[Suvremena lingvistika]] |volume=15 |location=Zagreb |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506101919/http://suvlin.ffzg.hr/index.php/suvlin/article/view/387/298 |archive-date=2009-05-06 |df= }}\n*{{citation |first=Mate